{{Short description|Legendary figure in Japanese mythology}}
[[Image:Tamamo-no-mae-woodblock.jpg|right|thumb|Tamamo-no-Mae Woodblock print by Tsukioka  [[Yoshitoshi]]]]

'''Tamamo-no-Mae''' ({{lang|ja|玉藻前}}, {{lang|ja|玉藻の前}}, also {{lang|ja|玉藻御前}}) is a legendary figure in [[Japanese mythology]]. One of the stories explaining the legend comes from [[:en:Muromachi period|Muromachi period]] (1336 to 1573) genre fiction called ''[[otogizōshi]]''. In the otogizōshi Tamamo-no-Mae was a [[:en:Courtesan|Courtesan]] under the Japanese [[:en:Emperor Konoe|Emperor Konoe]] (who reigned from 1142 through 1155).

Tamamo-no-Mae is believed to have been based on the historical empress consort [[:en:Fujiwara no Nariko|Fujiwara no Nariko]] (1117-1160), mother of Konoe, who participated in a number of succession struggles leading to the [[:en:Hōgen rebellion|Hōgen rebellion]] and [[:en:Heiji rebellion|Heiji rebellion]].{{sfnp|Marks|2023|p=107}} 

==Legends==
Stories of Tamamo-no-Mae being a legendary [[:en:Fox spirit|Fox spirit]] appear during the [[:en:Muromachi period|Muromachi period]] as [[otogizōshi]] (prose narratives), and were also mentioned by [[Toriyama Sekien]] in ''[[:en:Konjaku Hyakki Shūi|Konjaku Hyakki Shūi]]''. Edo period folklore then conflated the legend with similar foreign stories about fox spirits corrupting rulers, causing chaos in their territories.

